WEBVTT

00:22.890 --> 00:25.100
(country western music plays)
(engine idling)

00:25.100 --> 00:28.100
Hello. You ever hear
of this guy,

00:28.100 --> 00:29.560
Johnny Paycheck?

00:30.600 --> 00:32.430
No?

00:32.430 --> 00:34.640
You don't like
country music, do you?

00:34.640 --> 00:39.270
You think it's corny and twangy
and kind of stupid.

00:40.180 --> 00:41.640
Well, you could be right,

00:41.640 --> 00:43.930
but it's always good
to keep an open mind.

00:43.930 --> 00:47.470
You know, Johnny Paycheck here
sold over 10 million records.

00:47.470 --> 00:51.270
That's on par with people
like NWA and Gwen Stefani.

00:51.270 --> 00:53.520
In the early '90s once,
I was watching TV,

00:53.520 --> 00:56.220
and there was all this hubbub
on the news

00:56.220 --> 00:58.680
about NWA and gangsta rap

00:58.680 --> 01:00.470
and how it was
just too violent.

01:00.470 --> 01:01.640
I got tired of watching this,

01:01.640 --> 01:04.810
because I actually like NWA
and gangsta rap,

01:04.810 --> 01:06.980
so I switched over
to the Country Music Channel,

01:06.980 --> 01:09.640
where I saw Johnny Paycheck
being interviewed.
(country music plays)

01:09.640 --> 01:12.020
And he had
just gotten out of jail

01:12.020 --> 01:15.810
for shooting a guy,
like, he really shot a guy.

01:15.810 --> 01:19.680
And I thought,
"Why isn't anybody worried
about Johnny Paycheck?

01:19.680 --> 01:22.310
Why isn't Connie Chung
picking on him?"

01:22.310 --> 01:24.020
♪ Hey, Sharon Rae ♪

01:25.850 --> 01:27.680
♪ You are my life ♪

01:29.850 --> 01:32.310
♪ Wish I was half the man ♪

01:33.180 --> 01:34.560
♪ That you been a wife ♪

01:34.560 --> 01:36.680
Mike Judge:
Johnny Paycheck
was a dirt poor kid

01:36.680 --> 01:39.520
who pulled himself out
of poverty with his music,

01:39.520 --> 01:41.730
became a working-class hero,

01:41.730 --> 01:45.180
and almost killed himself
and one other person,

01:45.180 --> 01:47.770
that we know of,
in the process.

01:47.770 --> 01:50.770
And he looks a lot
like Charles Manson.

01:50.770 --> 01:53.680
(theme music playing)

02:05.770 --> 02:07.520
Mike: Greenfield, Ohio,

02:07.520 --> 02:10.180
birthplace of the detachable
horse collar,

02:10.180 --> 02:11.890
Johnny Paycheck,

02:11.890 --> 02:13.560
and these three guys,

02:13.560 --> 02:14.930
the Adams Brothers--

02:14.930 --> 02:17.520
Don, Gary, and Arnie--

02:17.520 --> 02:20.390
Paycheck's backup band
for nearly two decades.

02:20.390 --> 02:22.060
(country music playing)

02:22.060 --> 02:24.470
The first time I met
Johnny Paycheck,

02:24.470 --> 02:26.220
I was like four years old.

02:26.220 --> 02:28.100
One of my brothers
had him under a tree,

02:28.100 --> 02:29.560
kicking his butt.

02:29.560 --> 02:31.140
(guys laugh)

02:31.140 --> 02:32.560
We just hung out together,

02:32.560 --> 02:33.890
'cause we lived in the--

02:33.890 --> 02:36.100
the same neighborhood,
in the country.

02:36.100 --> 02:38.980
I remember one time
when he came to the house,

02:38.980 --> 02:40.310
he brought a guitar with him,

02:40.310 --> 02:44.520
and he sat in that kitchen
and sang and sang and sang.

02:44.520 --> 02:45.770
A couple years after that,

02:45.770 --> 02:47.890
me and Gary got in a talent show
in Greenfield,

02:47.890 --> 02:49.220
and we needed a guitar player,

02:49.220 --> 02:53.220
and so he played guitar
for us and, uh, and we lost.

02:53.220 --> 02:55.640
Gary:
Lost to a woman
that pantomimed,

02:55.640 --> 02:58.100
so that was rough to take.

02:58.100 --> 03:00.310
(guys laugh)

03:00.310 --> 03:02.470
Of course at that time,
he was Donny Lytle.

03:02.470 --> 03:03.600
(chuckles) Donny Lytle.

03:03.600 --> 03:05.310
He had several
different nicknames

03:05.310 --> 03:07.270
that a lot of people
would call him.

03:07.270 --> 03:09.430
In his youth, uh,
a lot of people

03:09.430 --> 03:11.600
referred to him as Hubcap Donny.

03:11.600 --> 03:14.680
Gary: He was a hubcap thief.

03:14.680 --> 03:16.140
Him stealing hubcaps,

03:16.140 --> 03:18.390
they forgot to mention
it had the car with it.

03:18.390 --> 03:20.560
Arnie:
Oh yeah.
(guys laugh)

03:20.560 --> 03:23.640
He had a little, uh,
criminal element to him.

03:23.640 --> 03:25.810
When he was
in Greenfield one time, uh,

03:25.810 --> 03:27.930
he went downtown
and, uh, got drunk,

03:27.930 --> 03:29.980
and he went
and broke into a car lot.

03:29.980 --> 03:32.430
Arnie: He seen the car
out there on the lot

03:32.430 --> 03:34.640
that he liked, so he went in
and found a key for it,

03:34.640 --> 03:37.350
took it for a drive
and didn't like it,

03:37.350 --> 03:40.220
so he brought it back,
went in, got another one.

03:40.220 --> 03:42.140
This time, he got
the whole key board.

03:42.140 --> 03:43.520
Don:
Stole all the keys.

03:43.520 --> 03:45.980
Arnie:
Got him another car,
took off again.

03:45.980 --> 03:47.430
(engine revs)

03:47.430 --> 03:49.060
Took it down
to Paint Creek...

03:49.060 --> 03:52.470
Don:
And took all the keys
and throwed 'em in the creek.

03:52.470 --> 03:54.020
He got in a little trouble
over that.

03:54.020 --> 03:56.890
Once he got out of jail,
he was gone.

03:56.890 --> 03:58.560
He took off for Nashville.

03:58.560 --> 03:59.810
Mike:
Down in Music City,

03:59.810 --> 04:02.390
Paycheck scraped by
as a backup musician,

04:02.390 --> 04:05.640
playing with everyone
from Porter Wagoner
to George Jones.

04:05.640 --> 04:08.310
Gary:
He was kind of like
a country music Mozart.

04:08.310 --> 04:10.430
You know,
he played guitar,
lead guitar,

04:10.430 --> 04:12.640
uh, steel, and, uh, drums.

04:12.640 --> 04:14.390
He was
an excellent bass player.

04:14.390 --> 04:17.220
Probably the best
in Nashville in his day.

04:17.220 --> 04:20.810
♪ Oh, this used to be ♪

04:20.810 --> 04:24.020
♪ Our favorite night spot ♪

04:24.020 --> 04:25.390
He was a great singer.

04:25.390 --> 04:30.020
♪ When she was here,
it was heaven ♪

04:30.020 --> 04:31.680
Gary:
Next time
I'd seen him was, uh,

04:31.680 --> 04:34.850
he had come back,
and he had changed
his name to Donny Young.

04:34.850 --> 04:38.140
Mike:
Donny Young wasn't exactly
burning up the charts...

04:38.140 --> 04:39.350
♪ ♪

04:39.350 --> 04:41.930
...so he decided
he would change his act.

04:41.930 --> 04:45.350
Gary:
Back in them days there
was a Johnny Dollar, and a...

04:45.350 --> 04:48.730
Arnie:
Johnny Cash and,
uh, Johnny Western.

04:48.730 --> 04:52.640
Mike: Donny's manager,
figuring he'd cash in
on the Johnny trend...

04:52.640 --> 04:54.980
(bell dings)
...recalled an obscure
Polish boxer,

04:54.980 --> 04:58.020
Johnny Paychek
with a "K."

04:58.020 --> 05:01.270
Gary:
From that point on,
I mean, he totally believed

05:01.270 --> 05:02.680
he was Johnny Paycheck.

05:02.680 --> 05:05.180
You couldn't talk him out of it.
Saying, "Okay, Donny."

05:05.180 --> 05:07.850
Or every time
you'd call him Donny,
he'd get mad at you.

05:07.850 --> 05:10.140
I think he had
an identity crisis.

05:10.140 --> 05:12.930
Mike:
He legally changed
his name to Johnny Paycheck,

05:12.930 --> 05:14.390
and his career took off,

05:14.390 --> 05:18.020
but deep down inside,
he was still Hubcap Donny.

05:18.020 --> 05:21.850
Paycheck was, uh, playing
with Patsy Cline.

05:21.850 --> 05:23.810
Patsy:
♪ Crazy ♪

05:23.810 --> 05:27.060
Mike: Paycheck stole
Patsy Cline's car.
♪ I'm crazy for feeling ♪

05:27.060 --> 05:29.600
I think that was-- that was
down in Texas someplace,

05:29.600 --> 05:33.020
a big country music park,
and he got to drinking.

05:33.020 --> 05:34.470
♪ ♪
(Arnie chuckles)

05:34.470 --> 05:36.890
He found her keys
and he just went out,

05:36.890 --> 05:39.060
got in her car,
and took off.

05:39.060 --> 05:40.600
(tires screech)

05:40.600 --> 05:42.140
And when he'd get
to the gate,

05:42.140 --> 05:45.180
they would shut
the gate on him.

05:45.180 --> 05:46.770
There was
only one entrance to it.

05:46.770 --> 05:48.430
They said,
"Just let him go.
He can't get out."

05:48.430 --> 05:51.890
And he went past that gate
a half a dozen times,

05:51.890 --> 05:54.270
and he just drove
around and around...

05:54.270 --> 05:56.770
(guys laughing)
...and around inside the park.

05:56.770 --> 05:58.140
(engine sputters)

05:58.140 --> 06:00.430
Arnie:
But eventually
it ran out of gas.

06:02.020 --> 06:05.680
He had a total
disregard for the law
when he was drinking.

06:05.680 --> 06:08.600
Mike:
Old habits die hard,

06:08.600 --> 06:10.930
but somehow he managed
to pick up a new one.

06:10.930 --> 06:14.640
There was, like, a couple
of 24-hour pharmacists

06:14.640 --> 06:16.730
there in Nashville,
you know what I mean.

06:16.730 --> 06:19.730
The drug of choice back then
was them Old Yellers.

06:19.730 --> 06:21.560
We'd go to the jam sessions,

06:21.560 --> 06:23.890
and Paycheck was always
up there playing bass.

06:23.890 --> 06:25.640
Well, we'd stay up
for three or four days

06:25.640 --> 06:28.470
just to get in tune,
and then jam for three
or four more.

06:28.470 --> 06:30.810
(horn honks)
Mike:
Between the speed binges

06:30.810 --> 06:32.350
and stints in jail,

06:32.350 --> 06:36.020
Paycheck found himself
broke and homeless.

06:36.020 --> 06:39.310
Then he met a man
named Swamp Dogg.

06:39.310 --> 06:42.100
(Swamp Dogg clears throat)
Umm...

06:43.810 --> 06:46.890
(burps) Excuse me.

06:46.890 --> 06:48.640
My song, I wrote,

06:48.640 --> 06:51.140
"Don't Take Her,
She's All I Got,"

06:51.140 --> 06:52.520
single-handedly

06:52.520 --> 06:55.600
put Johnny Paycheck
on the map,

06:55.600 --> 06:57.430
'cause he wasn't
nowhere near the map.

06:57.430 --> 07:00.980
♪ Let me tell you now, friend ♪

07:00.980 --> 07:03.730
♪ Don't take her,
she's all I've got ♪

07:05.350 --> 07:10.350
♪ Please don't take her love
away from me ♪

07:11.350 --> 07:13.390
♪ I'm begging you, friend ♪

07:13.390 --> 07:17.560
Swamp:
That single did
a shitload of sales.

07:17.560 --> 07:19.520
People were buying
the hell out of it.

07:19.520 --> 07:22.060
We made a fortune
with that motherfucker.

07:22.060 --> 07:24.270
But, anyway, I digress.

07:24.270 --> 07:28.270
Paycheck had a way
of destroying hisself
about every five years.

07:28.270 --> 07:30.060
I mean,
you could look for it.

07:30.060 --> 07:34.060
I mean any-- he'd get up,
things would be going
pretty smooth,

07:34.060 --> 07:36.390
and then he would--
he would just totally--

07:36.390 --> 07:38.470
he was hellbent
on self destruction.
Gary: Yeah, he did.

07:38.470 --> 07:40.180
He had a five-year cycle.

07:40.180 --> 07:41.850
Yeah, he had
about four of those.
Gary: Yeah.

07:41.850 --> 07:44.220
Yeah, and was
clean-cut, you know,

07:44.220 --> 07:45.930
and then
"Don't Take Her,
She's All I Got,"

07:45.930 --> 07:49.310
and he just as tame as--
doing everything like
a businessman,

07:49.310 --> 07:51.180
and then all of a sudden,
he put that hat on,

07:51.180 --> 07:54.730
and I thought, "Okay,
the five years is up.
I'm going home."

07:54.730 --> 07:56.020
(laughs)

07:56.020 --> 07:58.270
(yelling)
Gary:
We was in Canada,

07:58.270 --> 08:01.390
and Paycheck got drunk
and rowdy in the hotel there.

08:01.390 --> 08:02.640
(thuds)
(police sirens wail)

08:02.640 --> 08:05.060
So, the hotel people
called the police on him,

08:05.060 --> 08:07.850
and they come down
and they hauled him off.

08:07.850 --> 08:11.600
Anyhow, we went down
to get him out the next morning
and had to pay the fine.

08:11.600 --> 08:13.470
Paycheck didn't
even have a shirt on,

08:13.470 --> 08:15.100
had to go to court
without a shirt.

08:15.100 --> 08:17.730
♪ God save... ♪
I mean,
it was in Canada...

08:17.730 --> 08:20.930
♪ Our precious Queen ♪
...and that little deal there
where they all get up

08:20.930 --> 08:22.770
and all hail the queen,
something like that.

08:22.770 --> 08:25.470
Paycheck went,
"Fuck the queen."

08:25.470 --> 08:27.930
(guys laugh)

08:27.930 --> 08:30.270
I think Johnny Paycheck
was the real deal

08:30.270 --> 08:33.520
when it came down
to being a gangster,

08:33.520 --> 08:36.060
to being a thug,
and he could've...

08:36.060 --> 08:40.140
he could've been a Crip...
(laughs) very easily.

08:40.140 --> 08:42.890
We just did things
the way we wanted to,

08:42.890 --> 08:44.810
and, uh,
somebody didn't like it,

08:44.810 --> 08:46.350
we'd tell 'em
where to kiss it.

08:46.350 --> 08:48.850
Johnny...
didn't take no shit.

08:48.850 --> 08:51.100
Mike:
In October of 1976,

08:51.100 --> 08:53.060
Johnny released
what many considered to be

08:53.060 --> 08:55.560
the quintessential
outlaw country record,

08:55.560 --> 08:57.930
11 Months and 29 Days.

08:57.930 --> 08:59.560
This was a reference
to the length

08:59.560 --> 09:02.520
of his latest stint in prison
for check fraud.

09:02.520 --> 09:05.180
This charge earned him
a new nickname:

09:05.180 --> 09:07.060
Johnny Bad Check.

09:07.060 --> 09:08.980
A psychiatrist might
be able to figure out

09:08.980 --> 09:11.060
what caused
all Paycheck's troubles,

09:11.060 --> 09:12.930
but his friends have
their own theory.

09:12.930 --> 09:15.180
Paycheck was
a little feller.

09:15.180 --> 09:18.850
He was intimidated
by anybody over four feet tall.

09:18.850 --> 09:20.930
He had that little man complex.

09:20.930 --> 09:24.060
I guess he would have
a Napoleon complex,

09:24.060 --> 09:26.640
'cause he was short.
Hadn't been for that hat,

09:26.640 --> 09:28.680
he really would
have been short.

09:28.680 --> 09:31.600
Mike:
Paycheck's longtime manager,
Ernie Stepp,

09:31.600 --> 09:34.310
had to stick up for Johnny
on more than one occasion.

09:34.310 --> 09:37.640
If I'm working for you,
and if it's any way possible

09:37.640 --> 09:39.430
without killing somebody...

09:41.100 --> 09:42.810
I'll do it.

09:42.810 --> 09:45.100
One time,
we was coming out
of California,

09:45.100 --> 09:48.180
and, uh, John wanted
a-- a Big Mac.

09:48.180 --> 09:49.350
That's what he was wanting.

09:49.350 --> 09:51.770
He was coming down off
of drinking a little bit.

09:51.770 --> 09:53.390
I told the bus driver--

09:53.390 --> 09:55.600
I said, "John wants
a double-decker hamburger."

09:55.600 --> 09:58.220
Anyway, he stopped
at a truck stop,

09:58.220 --> 10:00.390
and that's where
we were gonna eat.

10:00.390 --> 10:02.520
I said, "No, uh,
John wants a--

10:02.520 --> 10:05.600
a different kind of sandwich,
a double triple hamburger."

10:05.600 --> 10:08.060
He said, no,
he's driving the fucking bus,

10:08.060 --> 10:10.020
we'll stop where he wants.

10:10.020 --> 10:14.680
John, he didn't come
out of the back of the bus
for food, cops, or nobody.

10:14.680 --> 10:17.520
Anyway, I shot
the bus driver in the ear.

10:17.520 --> 10:18.680
(gunshot)

10:18.680 --> 10:20.180
First I hit him
upside the head.

10:20.180 --> 10:23.680
I got him down on the--
on that front seat.

10:23.680 --> 10:26.100
Yes, they're easier to shoot
when you get 'em down.

10:26.100 --> 10:28.520
(laughs)
Yeah, if you--
if you don't get

10:28.520 --> 10:31.060
the right kind of sandwich
for me, I'll shoot you.

10:31.060 --> 10:32.520
(laughs)

10:32.520 --> 10:34.060
Mike:
Ernie not only made sure

10:34.060 --> 10:36.390
Paycheck got
his double triple hamburgers

10:36.390 --> 10:38.890
and kept his
bus driver in line,

10:38.890 --> 10:42.060
he also guided him
to the biggest moment
of his career.

10:42.060 --> 10:43.730
Ladies and gentlemen,
welcome, please,

10:43.730 --> 10:45.890
the fabulous
Johnny Paycheck!

10:45.890 --> 10:48.520
♪ Take this job and shove it ♪

10:48.520 --> 10:52.600
♪ I ain't working here
no more ♪

10:52.600 --> 10:55.770
That was a classic.
That's his signature song.

10:55.770 --> 10:59.560
It went to number one,
and the unemployment rate
skyrocketed.

10:59.560 --> 11:03.270
♪ You better not try
to stand in my way
as I'm walking ♪

11:03.270 --> 11:05.140
It was-- All of a sudden,
that's all you heard.

11:05.140 --> 11:06.890
It was like "Jingle Bells."

11:06.890 --> 11:09.430
♪ Take this job and shove it ♪

11:12.180 --> 11:13.680
(cheers, applause)

11:13.680 --> 11:16.770
It was the battle cry
of all the working people.

11:16.770 --> 11:19.220
John become
the working-class hero

11:19.220 --> 11:21.060
because that was
their slogan.

11:21.060 --> 11:23.390
The governor of West Virginia
decided to bring

11:23.390 --> 11:27.600
Johnny Paycheck in
to support the miners.

11:27.600 --> 11:29.930
Tom Brokaw:
It is blood that has made
Harlan County famous,

11:29.930 --> 11:33.930
blood spilled in some of the
most violent labor disputes
in this country's history.

11:33.930 --> 11:35.810
Newswoman:
People in these mountains
have guns,

11:35.810 --> 11:38.680
and violence on a picket line
is not unusual.

11:38.680 --> 11:41.140
As the strike dragged on
for more than a year,

11:41.140 --> 11:43.770
two miners were shot,
one man was killed.

11:43.770 --> 11:45.220
So they brought in, basically,

11:45.220 --> 11:46.600
an army of state troopers,

11:46.600 --> 11:49.020
and the state troopers lined up
and put a wall between 'em.

11:49.020 --> 11:50.600
And they said,
"If you come across the line,

11:50.600 --> 11:52.640
"we're arresting all of you,
and you're all going to jail,

11:52.640 --> 11:55.220
or we'll shoot it out with you."
And it was really tense.

11:55.220 --> 11:57.850
And all of a sudden,
right out in the middle
of the road,

11:57.850 --> 12:00.390
Paycheck walking out there
with a guitar, and he goes...

12:00.390 --> 12:02.430
♪ Take this job and shove it ♪

12:02.430 --> 12:05.140
(cheering)
Dub: And this crowd
just explode--

12:05.140 --> 12:07.640
I mean, the coal miners
just go insane.

12:09.810 --> 12:11.680
He was their hero.

12:11.680 --> 12:14.310
John spoke what
they couldn't speak.

12:14.310 --> 12:17.350
He was the reason why
they got the contract signed

12:17.350 --> 12:19.140
and the scabbers went home.

12:19.140 --> 12:22.810
That was the only time
I ever seen Paycheck cry.

12:22.810 --> 12:25.310
(cries)

12:25.310 --> 12:26.810
Damn.

12:26.810 --> 12:28.350
(chuckles)

12:29.810 --> 12:31.350
Mike:
For Johnny, the success

12:31.350 --> 12:33.020
of "Take This Job
and Shove It"

12:33.020 --> 12:36.020
had its highs...
and its highs.

12:36.020 --> 12:40.680
And the next thing I knew,
he was just a total cokehead.

12:40.680 --> 12:43.890
He was sucking a lot
of powder, a lot of it.

12:43.890 --> 12:47.390
We were driving down
the road in-- in the bus,

12:47.390 --> 12:50.100
and he'd run out
of cocaine.

12:50.100 --> 12:51.930
So he gets on the radio.

12:51.930 --> 12:55.520
He said, "Hey, out there,
breaker, breaker."  (laughs)

12:55.520 --> 12:58.020
He says,
"This is Johnny Paycheck.

12:58.020 --> 13:01.430
I want some cocaine
and don't care what it costs."

13:01.430 --> 13:03.600
(laughs)
(truck honks)

13:03.600 --> 13:06.680
So, here are
a couple of truckers,

13:06.680 --> 13:08.350
we're going down
the roads a way,

13:08.350 --> 13:11.060
and they were going
into a rest area.

13:11.060 --> 13:13.560
Gary:
These guys brought it back
and handed it to him,

13:13.560 --> 13:15.140
and they said,
"Here's your cocaine, man."

